The subfamily Geoplaninae of land planarians has a native distribution restricted to the Neotropical region and is currently composed of 25 genera ( Bulnes et al. 2018 ; Leal-Zanchet & Marques 2018 ), many of them being heterogeneous artificial groups awaiting revision (
Carbayo et al. 2013
). Among the well-defined genera, Cratera Carbayo et al ., 2013
and LuteostriataCarbayo, 2010 comprise 17 and 9 species respectively, all occurring in areas of the Atlantic Forest biome ( Carbayo 2010 ;
Carbayo et al. 2013
;
Rossi et al. 2014
, 2016 ; Carbayo & Almeida 2015 ; Negrete & Brusa 2016 ; Rossi & Leal-Zanchet 201 7; Lago-Barcia & Carbayo 2018 ).

Specimens of Cratera obsidiana sp. nov. were collected in the State Park of Turvo (27°00’ to 27°20’S , 53°40’ to 54°10’W ), a conservation unit in the northwestern border of the Brazilian state of Rio Grande do Sul and covered by deciduous seasonal forest ( Baptista & Leal-Zanchet 2010 ). Specimens of Luteostriata subtilis sp. nov. were collected from fragments of Araucaria moist forest of the National Park of Aparados da Serra (29°05’ to 29°15’S , 50°00’ to 50°15’ W ). This conservation unit is located at the eastern border of the Araucaria plateau in southern Brazil and shows two main phytophysiognomies: fragments of Araucaria moist forest surrounded by natural grasses of high altitudes and an area of dense ombrophilous forest at low altitudes (
Fick et al . 2006
).

