Luteostriata subtilis was the only species of its genus found in areas of Araucaria moist forest in the National Park of Aparados da Serra, in southern Brazil , during a study on the community structure of land flatworms between 2000 and 2002 (
Fick et al. 2006
). The species occurred with moderate abundance during this sampling period. It was not recorded in other areas of the Araucaria Plateau with the same phytophysiognomy, including the National Forest of São Francisco de Paula (
Leal-Zanchet et al. 2011
), the type-locality of other species of Luteostriata ( Froehlich & Leal-Zanchet 2003 ; Leal-Zanchet & Froehlich 2006 ; Lemos & Leal-Zanchet 2008 ).

Thus, both species seem to be endemic to their type-localities, as suggested by results from land flatworm inventories conducted in southern Brazil (
Carbayo et al. 2002
; Castro & Leal-Zanchet 2005 ;
Fick et al. 2006
;
Antunes et al. 2008
; Baptista et al. 2010;
Leal-Zanchet et al. 2011
;
Amaral et al. 2014
).
